idCitation.resTitle: Stopover Areas within the Sublette Mule Deer Herd Migration Corridor in the Upper Green River Basin of Wyoming, 1:24,000

citRespParty.rpOrgName: Karen Rogers, Wyoming Game and Fish Department, Staff Policy Analyst

dataIdInfo.idAbs: These data represent stopover areas within the Sublette herd migration corridor. Stopovers are places big game animals spend approximately 95% of their time to rest and forage during their migration travels. Habitat quality is likely higher in stopover areas. These habitats have been designated as 'Vital' to big game in the Wyoming Game and Fish Commission's Mitigation Policy.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: These data identify stopover areas within the migration corridor for the Sublette mule deer herd as designated by the Wyoming Game and Fish Department (WGFD).
dataIdInfo.idCredit: Wyoming Game and Fish Department (Karen Rogers, Scott Smith, Bob Lanka, Doug Brimeyer, Dean Clause), Wyoming Migration Initiative (Hall Sawyer), State of Wyoming

dataSource.srcDesc: The source data were BBMM statistical data based on GPS collar information.

prcStep.stepDesc: Raw polygons based on GPS data and processed using the Brownian-Bridge Movement Model were received by the WGFD for the three herd units separately researched. The three shapefiles were merged together, then clipped to the boundary of the designated corridor for the Sublette mule deer herd unit.
